The paper addresses the problem of mixed initiative, shared control for master-slave grasping and manipulation, which involves robotics (cs.RO) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The system proposed in the paper involves an autonomous agent assisting a human in teleoperating a remote slave arm/gripper, which requires human-computer interaction (cs.HC). The system also involves a-priori knowledge of the slave robot kinematics and desired post-grasp manipulative trajectory, which suggests a systems and control (cs.SY) aspect. Finally, the paper introduces a task-relevant velocity manipulability cost function, which involves machine learning (cs.LG) techniques.
